11 year old Billie Gilbert from Hobart recently rescued a draughtboard shark that was wedged between two rocks on low tide. 

Legend! Good on you, Billie! 👏❤️

🎥: Abby Gilbert

Follow us for more👇🏻
@UnderWaterStuffs 💙

node.text:
Bottlenose dolphins are filmed apparently getting high on secretions from pufferfish. The pufferfish secrete a neurotoxin that in high doses can kill but in small doses seemingly have a narcotic effect.

Video: 'Dolphins - Spy in the Pod' narrated by David Tennant
.
.
.
#SpyinthePod #Dolphins #pod  #puffa #fish #underthesea #wildlife #nature #marine #life #behaviour #wild #science #storytelling #NaturalHistory

node.title: Dolphins On Drugs - Pass The Puffer

node.text:
This is truly one of the greatest spontaneous encounters we've seen. We were lucky enough to receive all the raw footage and hear the entire story, a special thanks to @luisorozcoa 🙏
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
When we asked how it all happened he said "As we heard "Orcas" on the radio, adrenaline and excitement started to run through my entire body, I have never seen them before"
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
His words "I was the first one to get in the water, it was freaking cold but I didn't feel anything because of the adrenaline.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
With poor visibility I dived under and was swimming towards nothing until out of nowhere the KING OF THE OCEAN approached me!
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
I dived following one of the orcas when suddenly another one came up blowing bubbles! Never have I seen orcas getting that close to a diver"
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
When we asked him about his experience he said " My mind was almost in shock, It was a one time lifetime experience so there was no room for fear in my mind, I was living the moment full in adrenaline."
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
When the big one came over him and dived right into his face, he could feel the clicks hitting his body.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
He said "Making eye contact with the apex predator of the ocean was the strongest feeling I've ever had, there I did not see a monster but a curious being, just like a child" 😍
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
This spectaculair encounter lasted about 10 minutes
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀
©️: @luisorozcoa
With @segeljungs & @bajaadventureco
Via: @savingthewaves

node.title: Face to face with the Apex of the ocean

node.text:
This sad but ultimately uplifting video of a seal rescued from being trapped in fishing net helps to show why over 1 million marine animals — dolphins, fish, sharks, turtles and birds — are killed each year due to plastic debris in the ocean as kind police officers like this aren’t always around to cut these poor animals free from the nets that trap them. There‘s an estimated 100 million tons of plastic in oceans around the world...and nearly half of that plastic waste is fishing nets like this! We are determined to stop this madness before it’s too late, especially considering there’s even more #plasticpollution on land too and spreading awareness about this crisis is the first step so please share this video with your followers and tag people in the comments who need to be made aware of this situation ASAP! It’s we the people who must influence corporations and governments to change their behavior and laws so it’s crucial we WORK TOGETHER ASAP to make this a world that’s safe for humans and animals alike! Will you join us in this fight and help us spread awareness? 
Great video by: Steven Hill
Text via: @savethereef

node.text:
Bottlenose dolphins are filmed apparently getting high on secretions from pufferfish. The pufferfish secrete a neurotoxin that in high doses can kill but in small doses seemingly have a narcotic effect.

Video: 'Dolphins - Spy in the Pod' narrated by David Tennant
.
.
.

node.text: ⚠️URGENT PROBLEM RIGHT NOW ⚠️ PLEASE SHARE! ❗️❗️8 million tons of plastic are dumped into our rivers and oceans every year & we humans consume, unknowingly, roughly the size of a credit card in microplastics EVERY week! By 2030, there will be more plastic than fish in our oceans, all while killing our marine life, wildlife and environment and all this plastic has begun causing major health problems for humans so we must make EVERYONE aware of how bad this crisis is right now! Sadly, this crisis has gotten even worse since the pandemic began in 2020 as the production and use of single-use plastics has increased exponentially this year, and with all the poor waste management systems and overwhelmed recycling facilities around the world, more single use plastic waste is ending up in our rivers and oceans than EVER before! This is a pivotal time in human history and for our planet and it’s we the people who hold the power to fix this before it’s too late in a few years by demanding an end to single-use plastics and refusing to buy anymore plastic TODAY! Please share this URGENT post with your followers and tag people, celebrities, influencers and news media who need to see it and tell them to share it too and let’s all wok together to end plastic pollution RIGHT NOW…remember there is no planet B! Video by @amirzakeri #endplasticpollution #plasticfree #plasticpollution #savethereef #stopsingleuseplastic Via: @karmagawa

node.text:
We humans kill thousands of sharks every hour all over the world and because they are an apex predator, removing these animals from the marine ecosystem is having a disastrous effect on our oceans and all marine life. Too few people realize it, and the consequences soon will be devastating so we must make more people aware of this problem RIGHT NOW! Please share this sad video with your followers and tag people who need to see it...we must do better before it’s too late and time is running out!
Video by @tundeednut

node.text:
Rainbow Island, Iran 🇮🇷 The soil composing Hormuz Island in #Iran is highly concentrated with Iron Oxide. This concentration leads to red coloration, which is washed up in the waves.
Have you ever seen anything like this?

📽 @elhamgholami
📍 Hormuz, Iran
